Liquid clustering — operational, not just on-disk.

We met liquid clustering earlier as the modern replacement for partitioning plus zorder. Here's the operational angle the exam tests.

The pre-liquid layout decision was one-shot. You picked the partition column up front, and if you got it wrong, re-partitioning meant a full rewrite of terabytes of data. Zorder helped with co-location within partitions, but the partitioning itself stayed fixed.

Liquid clustering changes that dynamic. You declare the columns the table is clustered on, delta organises the data into clusters that can be incrementally re-balanced, and you can change the keys later without rewriting the world. So a table clustered on customer id and time today can be re-clustered on merchant category three months later when query patterns shift.

What it buys you operationally is four things — no small-files-per-partition problem, because directories aren't the unit of organisation any more; no skew when one partition is a hundred times larger, because clusters re-balance; the ability to evolve the keys as queries change; and it pairs naturally with predictive optimization. That's why it's the recommended default for new delta tables.
